In July and August 2004, devastating floods in Bangladesh claimed over 700 lives and submerged 38% of the country, displacing millions.
Monsoon rains and Himalayan snowmelt caused major rivers like the Ganges and Brahmaputra to overflow, marooning 200,000 people.
Landslides in Chittagong killed 126, while millions fled their homes in India, Bangladesh, and Nepal due to heavy rains.
The situation worsened as rivers burst their banks, forcing evacuations and relief efforts.
